ting Statement. The term \u2018CITES trade data\u2019 refers to data from CITES Annual Reports as provided by the Parties and managed by UNEP-WCMC on behalf of the CITES Secretariat. Where information has been provided from a particular country\u2019s official trade statistics, this has been specified. ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS AND CREDITS Many individuals and institutions contributed to the review of the CITES amendment proposals and compilation of the present Analyses. Those to whom we would first like to extend our thanks are the reviewers of these proposals, many of them members of the IUCN Species Survival Commission (SSC) Specialist Groups, as well as the many other scientists and experts from other institutions who, although not formally linked with SSC, have volunteered their time and expertise to this process. Dena Cator led on the fundraising, without which we would not have been able to undertake this work. We again acknowledge the generous support of all our funders in these economically difficult times. The staff members of TRAFFIC, who assisted in the review of proposals, deserve recognition for the contribution they have made to this document. We would also like to thank the French translation team of Daniele and Richard Devitre, and the Spanish translation team made up of Wendy Byrnes, Ana Bennett and Carlos Ibero. The Analyses team was made up of: Thomasina Oldfield, Willow Outhwaite, Dan Challender, Vicki Crook, Louisa Musing, Anastasiya Timoshyna, and Bryony Morgan and a number of consultants, including: Martin Jenkins, Emma Brooks, Janine Robinson, Sue Wells and Catherine Rutherford, Richard Jenkins, Steven Broad and Richard Thomas provided a great deal of support and valuable input into the Analyses, especially through the sign off process. Willow Outhwaite and Kim Lochen designed the cover. Those responsible for overseeing the project were Martin Jenkins and Thomasina Oldfield who accept responsibility for the contents of this document. iii Contents CoP